## Plan quality audit

Before treating this plan as ready, ask explicitly. Each "no" is a candidate gap to fix before starting execution.

- [ ] Did I compare against the strongest similar existing plan in this codebase (or a previous project), not just start from memory?
- [ ] Are later slices at least as well-specified as earlier slices? (Common failure: late slices are vague placeholders.)
- [ ] Does the plan force alternative-search, not just execution? (Did I consider 2+ approaches per slice?)
- [ ] Does it force adversarial review at slice boundaries? (Milestone gates do this — confirm they're real, not pro-forma.)
- [ ] Does each slice have a frozen `Output`, `Decision`, and `Evidence to close` — or are any silently missing?
- [ ] Are the damage-prevention AND value-preservation gates BOTH specified, not just one?
- [ ] Are runtime / monitoring expectations stated as an exact contract, or only in spirit?
- [ ] Are output artifacts NAMED, not implied?
- [ ] Are blocked same-time changes explicitly listed? (i.e., what work CANNOT happen during this plan to avoid interference.)
- [ ] Does the plan still match actual project state, or has it drifted? (Re-check at each session start per the task-decomposition procedure's Phase 3.)

If any answer is "no" or "I don't know," the plan is probably still too thin. Fix before treating execution as authorized.
